    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Bigger Oil Better?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fariborz Ghadar letter comments on October 16 article on acquisition of Texaco by Chevron</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Chevron Agrees to Buy Texaco for Stock Valued at $36 Billion'' (front page, Oct. 16):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Chevron Agrees to Buy Texaco for Stock Valued at $36 Billion'' (front page, Oct. 16):</p>
        <p>Here we go again: another mega-merger to cut costs and enhance profitability. But bigger is not always better.</p>
        <p>Our study in the Harvard Business Review shows that few of the huge, cross-border mergers reshaping industries like oil have resulted in complete domination.</p>
        <p>We studied 20 industries from 1950 to 1999 and found that niche players, low-cost producers and small companies using new technology eventually evolve and take small but critical shares of their markets.</p>
        <p>There are alternative strategies available; in an era that is witnessing technological discontinuities, managers must not focus so much on size as a goal but rather on the development of new business models that help them compete.</p>
        <p>FARIBORZ GHADAR  University Park, Pa., Oct. 17, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is director of the Center for Global Business Studies, Pennsylvania State University.</p>
      </block>
